// TEST: exec_generic_record
// EXPECT: output "42;hi;42"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust, go
//
// Generic record (`record Box[T] { value: T }`) codegen: a type-parameterized
// value type, constructed at two distinct instantiations (`Box[Int]` and
// `Box[String]`), read back via field access, and read back via a generic
// method (`fn get(self) -> T`).
//
// Originally the regression fixture for the Python generics defect (DV12,
// Python slice): `record Box[T]` emitted `class Box:` with a field annotation
// `value: T` and no `T = TypeVar("T")` / `Generic[T]`, so the module raised
// `NameError: name 'T' is not defined` at class-evaluation time. The fix emits
// `T = TypeVar("T")` once per type parameter (deduped within the file), adds
// `Generic[T, …]` to the class bases, and imports `TypeVar`/`Generic`.
//
// `go` is now included (codegen-completeness P1-b2 / DV12): Go's generic
// construction now emits the explicit instantiation `Box[int64]{…}` (Go does
// not infer struct type args from composite-literal fields) and the generic
// method receiver emits `func (self *Box[T]) ...`. The generic-method half also
// fixed the TS declaration-merge (`interface Box<T>`) and Rust `impl<T> Box<T>`
// (with a synthesized `T: Clone` bound + `self.value.clone()` for the
// field-returning getter).
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

record Box[T] {
  value: T
}

impl Box {
  fn get(self) -> T {
    return self.value
  }
}

fn main() -> Void {
  let n = Box { value: 42 }
  let s = Box { value: "hi" }
  println("${n.value};${s.value};${n.get()}")
}
